  "prompt": "What're the differences between cooking eggs certain ways?",
  "response": "Here are some common egg cooking methods and their differences:\n\n1. Sunny-side up\n- Cooked on one side only\n- Egg white is set, yolk remains liquid\n- Not flipped during cooking\n\n2. Over easy\n- Flipped once\n- Yolk remains runny\n- Both sides briefly cooked\n\n3. Over medium\n- Flipped once\n- Yolk is partially cooked, slightly firm\n- More cooked than over easy\n\n4. Over hard\n- Flipped once\n- Yolk is completely cooked and solid\n- No liquid remaining in yolk\n\n5. Scrambled\n- Beaten eggs mixed while cooking\n- Soft, fluffy texture\n- No distinct yolk or white\n\n6. Poached\n- Cracked into simmering water\n- No shell, no added fat\n- Soft, delicate texture\n- Yolk remains runny\n\n7. Hard-boiled\n- Cooked in shell in boiling water\n- Entire egg is solid\n- Can be peeled and eaten\n\n8. Soft-boiled\n- Cooked in shell in boiling water\n- Whites are set, yolk remains runny\n- Often served in egg cup\n\nEach method offers different textures, flavors, and cooking experiences.",
